english:
  title: 'Inscription on the Picture of Eight Steeds: with Preface'
  author: Seong Sam-mun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    After bitter frost comes warm spring; beneath turbulent rapids lies a deep pool. Order and chaos succeed one another—it is thus in ancient times and now. Once Goryeo's fortune waned and Heaven's mandate departed. Hierarchy dissolved, jackals seized power, and martial virtue gave way to indulgence. War descended upon the fields, and the foolish masses wallowed in suffering. The stag of Qin was lost—the age of grasping had ended. Without a Yu to fish us out, who could bear the burden of salvation?

    Then came our Great Ancestor, the Kangheong, Jeorin, Gyeun, Seongmun, Shinmun Great King—one who answered the call of a thousand years, bearing the gifts of supreme sagehood. Truly Heaven-sent virtue, counseling with spirits. With a single flash of wrath he drove out the demon monks, and the state stood firm. With ten thousand plans he crushed the Red Bandits, and the ancestral temples remained. He pursued the Nayus, conquered the Wulie—easier than pressing Mount Tai upon an egg. He battled at Jirisan, triumphed at Unfung—as effortless as wind sweeping leaves.

    At the Rabbit Cave he loosened his saddle; noxious vapors dispersed at the ocean's edge. At the Yalu he turned his bridle; great righteousness shone bright as sun and stars. Through sixty battles his steps barely touched ground—like Han Gaozu's restless march. Across ten thousand miles his thighs never thinned—unlike Shu's Xianzhu. South he struck; north submitted. The great trembled; the small waited. Wherever he went, all rejoiced together. Thus was his work accomplished.

    After five hundred years the sage appears. Seven virtues have measured five hundred years. At three thousand steeds the divine creature manifested. One heart perfectly harmonized three thousand. His galloping matched the measure of heaven's law, his gentle nature bent all people to his will. Longing for the camp, wisdom overcame the maze. Today's trials yield to diligent effort. My whip points—the crossing is assured. Heavy is the trust of life and death; brighter shines the glory of civil and martial achievement. Majestic as the plains of Zhou, glorious as the stallions of Lu—can they be surpassed?

    The Supreme One gathered essence; the Heavenly Treasure revealed its value. The Nine-Five rode the times, answering the constancy of Earth with endless blessing. Bow and arrow rest in quiver; groans transform into song. Southern barbarians seek passage; northern peoples don ornaments. Ten thousand ages of unwrapped virtue—Heaven's blessings reach unto this day. The Three Hans are pacified; we rest at ease. What power has the ruler over me?

    Though this flows from divine-martial force and the effect of swift-galloping steeds, things lack wisdom; it was time that granted the opportunity. Our Lord, the Crown Prince, inherits Heaven's brilliance, continues his ancestors' great luminescence. Bearing heavy responsibility, he thinks to open the future without break. In performing coronation rites, he vows never to forget the succession. He reverences his forebears' labors, forever yearns for their wisdom. He knows that imperial fortune cannot succeed alone—it requires the harmony of able men. Thus the oath of mutual loyalty runs deep; the debt of benevolence towers high.

    Once the assembled princes were painted on the Cloud Terrace. Yet the Eight Steeds had no place at the Mausoleum of Brilliance. Therefore the decree was issued, the painting commissioned. Tiger-headed brushwork blazes forth, dragon-jawed forms leap from the sea. Crimson streams mark the spine—the labor of sweat appears tangible. White arrows pierce red flesh—the heat of battle lingers. Each stroke can resurrect dead bones; to gaze upon it is to be warned. Let descendants, in leisure, observe this picture and understand that riches came from the saddle. Resting on silk cushions, they shall remember wind-combing and rain-bathing days. Feasting on eight delicacies, they shall recall simple fare. Compare this to the moral mirrors of bronze vessels—do not exchange it for painted mountains and waters. Then shall this one scroll of the Eight Steeds of the Great East rank alongside the Seven Months of the Odes' Bin section, moving together in eternal harmony. What glory this is!

    Yet see: the flying bird strikes the shore; the startled rat brings down the chariot. Zhou's King Mu feasted the Queen Mother of the West; carriage tracks wound round the world. Han's army besieged the Two Commanders; flying transport reached beyond the borders. Many horses brought no safety to Jin; a thousand steeds gave no glory to Qi. Some lost their purpose and sullied their virtue; some exhausted their people and sickened the state. All these abandoned the way of kings, becoming mere objects of later laughter.

    Alack! Under Tang, loyalty; under Sui, flattery—yet men are the same. Used, the horse becomes a tiger; unused, a rat. Can we marvel at material things? When later rulers view this picture, let them model themselves on their imperial ancestors, heed the lessons of kings gone before. Morning and evening, let this thought not depart their minds. Then shall it be true blessing for our Korea through ten thousand ages.

    I have heard: to glorify ancestors is the height of filial piety; to illuminate posterity is the great work of teaching. Good deeds unknown are not bright; known truths untransmitted are not kind. I observe that our Crown Prince perfects reverence, elevates his forebears, and extends benevolence to all things. He honors what ancestors honored, cherishes what ancestors cherished, pouring into this hour his yearning heart. Endless beauty achieved, yet endless care maintained—this is the rule descendants must guard. Filial duty and reverence ascend together; wisdom and benevolence unite as one. The time for song and praise has come; how can we remain silent?

    Yet my talent is but a stumbling donkey's; my learning cannot clarify the confusion of fish-words. In seeking the wise at Yan's tower, I blush at my thousand-li insufficiency. At Han's court of waiting artists, I undeservedly gained a glance. Though dull and unfit for distant journeys, a cock's crow and dog's bark have their purpose. How much more so to embellish sacred deeds—this is my duty. Let me exhaust this humble effort in serving filial thought, singing of the steed's virtue to the ten-thousandth part, broadcasting great blessings to ages yet to come. Respectfully I bow and present this inscription:

    Horizontal-Cloud Colt—steady and stalwart!—
    ten thousand miles, thousand-gold bones.
    Darting past obstacles, vanishing like mist,
    four hooves never stumbled once.
    Our sovereign labored through wind and storm;
    how many perils crossed together!
    From this great foundation laid comes today—
    Horizontal-Cloud, your deeds rank first.

    Gliding Linden Green—ridgeline peaks your back—
    earthly kind, metallic bright.
    Gentle strength, auspice of sage and clear rule,
    ages lengthened, skills perfected.
    Four times you brought proud realms to submission;
    thirty-one reigns your spirit has graced.
    Death left stone tomb with name undying—
    Gliding Linden, your virtue stands praised.

    Pursuing-Wind Raven—from Hu lands came—
    treasure of the realm, none match it.
    Soaring on sound, chasing sun through half-sky,
    one glimpse earned the sovereign's heart.
    Through peril and danger you journeyed with men,
    aiding divine-martial might to clear the land.
    Your deeds match Zhaoling's White Emperor's work—
    Pursuing-Wind, destiny's pattern fulfilled.

    Flashing-Crimson Dragon—horse or dragon?
    few match such martial skill.
    Your shadow turns; your cry rings out—
    ten thousand steeds of the north all bow.
    Your gallop moves in perfect measure,
    one whip's gesture sealed the realm.
    Ten thousand ages of the Great East rest secure—
    Flashing-Crimson speaks truth indeed.

    Dragon-Soaring Purple—young Heaven's Horse—
    lightning gleams from eyes; tubes form ears.
    Inhering lunar essence, gathering river qi,
    you bore our true dragon, changed like spirits.
    In battle's press you bore life and death,
    once leapt through muddy shallows.
    Your feat matches Dialu's leap at Tan Waters—
    Dragon-Soaring, ten thousand ages you shall shine.

    Congealed-Frost White—not strength alone—
    large, strong, and wise together.
    The Yalu flows vast; its banks climb thousand feet;
    white arrows flash bright with crimson bow.
    Night-lamp's brilliance burns all around;
    flagged formations follow your hooves.
    Single leap freed Three Hans from torment—
    Congealed-Frost White, your grace endures.

    Lion-Hued Yellow—ever wandering boundless—
    chancellor bright, general strong.
    Heaven gathers qi to show its blessing;
    the Dragon-Steed surges through ocean's heart.
    Tower-high Duryu blazes with rebel spite;
    one bound, your blade-flash arose.
    Enemy heads lay heaped like mountains—
    Lion-Hued, your wisdom is vast.

    Mystic Leopard—fierce and unflinching—
    without rival, what stands for contest?
    Fang-Star poured forth its essence into hidden splendor;
    extraordinary hooves leapt most wondrously.
    At Rabbit Cave you finished the battle, showed strange effect—
    no island raiders' boats found return.
    On silk your form blazes sharp and clear—
    Mystic Leopard—marvelous indeed!
